In 1971, Bob Thomas wrote Creeper for ARPANET as an experiment in self-replication, and it displayed the message, “I’m the creeper, catch me if you can,” which is annoyingly on-brand for malware history.
The 1988 Morris Worm was not meant to melt the early internet, but a design flaw made it spread far too aggressively, disrupting roughly 10 per cent of connected machines and giving incident response an early baptism.
Cross-Site Scripting is older than many junior analysts’ careers; the term became widely used in the late 1990s, and the bug class still survives because browsers remain extremely trusting little optimists.
Attackers regularly use valid admin tools such as PowerShell, PsExec and Remote Desktop Protocol because detection is harder when the command history looks less like malware and more like Tuesday.
Business Email Compromise often works without malware at all; one convincing invoice change or fake executive payment request can do more damage than a noisy trojan and generate far less telemetry.
In cloud environments, an over-permissioned identity is often more dangerous than a missing patch, because one bad role assignment can turn a minor foothold into broad access with beautifully legitimate logs.
Public-key cryptography solved the old problem of sharing secrets at scale; Diffie and Hellman’s 1976 paper was one of the quiet moments where mathematics did more for security than another firewall ever could.
One of the most cited Internet of Things breach stories involved a casino where attackers reportedly pivoted through a smart fish-tank thermometer, because apparently even the aquarium needed a threat model.
The first known personal-computer virus, Brain, appeared in 1986 and infected boot sectors on IBM-compatible floppy disks, helpfully including the authors’ contact details as if this were normal customer support.
Melissa, in 1999, spread through Microsoft Word macros and mass-mailed itself via Outlook, proving that email-borne chaos was already mature before most people had stopped saying “surfing the web.”
Heartbleed, disclosed in 2014 as CVE-2014-0160, was caused by a missing bounds check in OpenSSL and could leak chunks of process memory, which is a painfully efficient way to embarrass the word “secure.”
Threat actors love delay-based evasion: sleep timers, staged payloads and bursty command-and-control all exist partly to avoid short sandbox windows and partly to waste everyone’s afternoon.
Adversary-in-the-Middle phishing kits do not need to break Multi-Factor Authentication cryptographically; they proxy the session, steal the token, and let the user do the hard work for them.
DNS is both crucial and oddly forgiving; a single bad record, expired domain or forgotten subdomain delegation can create security issues that look exotic until you realise it was paperwork.
Kerckhoffs’s principle, from the nineteenth century, says a cryptosystem should stay secure even if everything except the key is public, which remains a useful corrective to security by wishful thinking.
In 2015, a US teenager breached former CIA Director John Brennan’s AOL account through social engineering, which is a reminder that even high-profile targets can still be defeated by basic identity abuse.
The 2000 ILOVEYOU worm spread via a Visual Basic Script attachment named like a love letter and caused global damage, largely because curiosity remains a stable protocol regardless of patch level.
Stuxnet, uncovered in 2010, targeted industrial control systems and manipulated Siemens programmable logic controllers while reporting normal conditions, which was a grim milestone in cyber-physical sabotage.
SQL injection has been ruining developers’ days for decades because untrusted input plus dynamic queries still equals unauthorised database access, no matter how modern the framework looks.
Ransomware operators often exfiltrate data before encryption now because extortion works better when they can threaten disclosure as well as downtime; criminals do love layered revenue streams.
Smishing campaigns work partly because SMS lacks the visual cues users rely on in email, and mobile screens are excellent at hiding the sort of details defenders would rather people noticed.
The Server Message Block version 1 protocol lingered in many estates long after it should have retired, which helped keep EternalBlue relevant in the way asbestos remains historically relevant.
Hashing is not encryption; a password hash is meant to be hard to reverse, whereas encryption is specifically designed to be reversed with the right key, a distinction that continues to need repeating.
A spelling mistake once helped expose a fake banking site because the phisher registered a lookalike domain that forgot which brand it was impersonating halfway through the landing page.
The 1983 film WarGames did more for public cyber awareness than many policy papers, even if the operational details were theatrical and the password guessed from a dead scientist was slightly inconvenient.
Conficker, first seen in 2008, infected millions of Windows systems and used multiple propagation methods, including weak passwords and a patched vulnerability, which is about as flattering to asset management as it sounds.
Shellshock, disclosed in 2014, affected Bash and allowed trailing commands in crafted environment variables, turning a deeply boring shell feature into remote code execution with remarkable efficiency.
Initial access brokers exist because many crews prefer buying footholds instead of earning them, which is basically outsourcing for criminals with the same disappointing market logic as everything else.
Spear-phishing gets more effective when the lure contains something operationally plausible, such as a policy update, invoice query or shared document request, rather than a prince with an urgent wire transfer.
The Capital One breach in 2019 showed how a cloud misconfiguration plus Server-Side Request Forgery and over-permissive Identity and Access Management could expose more than 100 million records.
One-Time Passwords are better than just passwords, but they are still phishable, which is why phishing-resistant methods such as FIDO2 matter whenever the estate and user tolerance allow it.
In one notable arrest, a malware author reportedly used the same handle in underground forums and elsewhere online, because operational security is often strongest right up until it encounters ego.
The first widely recognised antivirus products emerged in the late 1980s and early 1990s, when signature-based detection made sense in a world where malware families were slower-moving and less allergic to identification.
Code Red, in 2001, exploited Microsoft Internet Information Services and defaced websites while launching denial-of-service activity, reminding organisations that web servers are not magically safer because they serve useful things.
BlueKeep, CVE-2019-0708, was alarming because it was wormable and pre-authentication in Remote Desktop Services, which is the sort of phrase that makes patch windows suddenly seem more negotiable.
Living-off-the-land activity often includes discovery through native commands, lateral movement with built-in protocols and persistence through scheduled tasks, because defenders unfortunately use the same operating system.
QR-code phishing, or quishing, works by shifting scrutiny from the desktop to the phone, where security controls and user suspicion are often thinner and the camera does the clicking for them.
Content Delivery Networks help performance and resilience, but they also give attackers useful camouflage because not every request to a trusted service is as wholesome as its hostname suggests.
The Caesar cipher was broken long before modern computing, which is useful perspective whenever someone tries to describe obscurity as an advanced protection strategy.
The “you have been hacked” email scam often includes an old leaked password to create panic, which is less black magic than recycling from the internet’s giant bargain bin of breached credentials.
In 1989, the AIDS Trojan was distributed on floppy disks and demanded payment by post to a Panama mailbox, which feels quaint until you remember it was still extortion.
Zeus, first identified in 2007, specialised in banking credential theft and inspired countless variants, partly because crimeware builders appreciate reusable code almost as much as legitimate developers do.
Directory traversal remains effective because applications continue to mishandle path input, letting attackers request files they were never meant to see by being very specific about where not to stop.
Many intrusions include hands-on-keyboard reconnaissance for backups, security tooling and privileged groups before anything noisy happens, because even criminals prefer not to trip alarms before they know where the exits are.
Consent phishing targets users’ willingness to approve cloud app permissions, which can be more reliable than stealing passwords and far less dependent on whether somebody finally enabled Multi-Factor Authentication.
The Border Gateway Protocol trusts announcements more than comfort allows, so route hijacks and leaks remain a reminder that the internet’s plumbing still runs on a surprising amount of professional courtesy.
Salt in password storage matters because identical passwords should not produce identical hashes; otherwise your database becomes a very efficient pattern-recognition exercise for whichever criminal downloads it next.
A Japanese police department once warned that cybercriminals had hidden malware in adult-game mods, which is one of several cases where embarrassment was apparently considered part of the access-control model.
The Cuckoo’s Egg by Cliff Stoll is still worth reading because it captures slow-burn investigation work, accounting oddities and the maddeningly human pace of tracing intrusions in the pre-hype era.
CryptoLocker, which surged in 2013, helped normalise ransomware as a business model by combining strong encryption with scalable distribution, proving again that the worst innovations are often operational rather than technical.
Return-Oriented Programming became famous for bypassing exploit mitigations by chaining existing code snippets, which is what happens when Memory Corruption meets a particularly stubborn talent for improvisation.
Attackers frequently disable logging, tamper with event retention or clear shell history after privilege escalation, because stealth is easier when the evidence has had an unfortunate accident.
MFA fatigue attacks exploit repeated push notifications until a user approves one out of confusion or irritation, effectively turning impatience into an authentication factor.
Amazon Web Services instance metadata became a recurring concern because internal metadata services were never meant to be internet-facing treasure chests accessed through badly filtered web requests.
The Enigma machine was formidable for its day, but cryptography history repeatedly shows that strong maths can still be undone by key management, predictable procedure and human shortcuts.
A fake antivirus pop-up once convinced users to pay for malware removal from malware it had installed itself, which is impressively circular even by cybercrime standards.
The 1999 Melissa outbreak made many organisations reconsider macro security, attachment handling and the general wisdom of trusting Word documents that arrive with enthusiasm but no context.
Mydoom, in 2004, spread through email and peer-to-peer networks and became one of the fastest-spreading worms of its time, because apparently mass-mailing nonsense was a growth market.
Log4Shell, CVE-2021-44228, demonstrated how a single logging library could create widespread remote code execution exposure, which is a brutal outcome for something intended merely to write helpful messages.
Domain generation algorithms let malware cycle through huge numbers of potential command-and-control domains, forcing defenders into the sort of coordination exercise registrars were not put on earth to enjoy.
Attackers increasingly abuse OAuth app registration and token theft because cloud identity is where trust accumulates, and nothing says “authorised” like a malicious token with valid claims.
Containers share a kernel unless isolated differently, which means a container escape is not merely a neat conference slide but a direct route to a very awkward root-cause meeting.
Claude Shannon’s work turned cryptography into an information-theory discipline rather than a bag of clever tricks, which is another way of saying the maths people arrived and ruined everyone’s excuses.
One scammer was caught after using a mule account in his own name, which is a crisp reminder that not every adversary is a disciplined operator from an intelligence-service brochure.
The notion of “computer virus” was popularised in the 1980s, though self-replicating concepts appeared earlier in fiction and research, because the industry took a while to settle on suitable biological metaphors.
Emotet evolved from banking trojan to malware delivery platform and became notorious for email-thread hijacking, which made malicious replies look unpleasantly legitimate.
Spectre and Meltdown, revealed in 2018, exploited speculative execution side effects in modern processors, showing that hardware performance tricks can become security liabilities with a very expensive blast radius.
Scheduled tasks, registry run keys and startup folders remain common persistence methods because they are simple, available and frequently indistinguishable from ordinary system administration until context catches up.
Attackers who compromise a supplier email account can invoice multiple customers from a genuinely trusted thread, which is why third-party compromise is often more convincing than direct impersonation.
Software supply chains now include package repositories, build pipelines, signing systems and update channels, so “we trust the vendor” has become less a control and more a lifestyle choice.
Perfect Forward Secrecy matters because if a long-term key is later compromised, past sessions should still remain unreadable, which is one of the few places paranoia ages well.
Researchers once found exposed baby monitors speaking to the internet with almost no security, because unfortunately “cute” has never been a reliable control family.
The World Wide Web appeared in 1989, and security was not part of the original design priority, which explains rather a lot about the next few decades.
WannaCry erupted in May 2017 using the EternalBlue exploit against Server Message Block version 1, and it hit hospitals, manufacturers and governments with the subtlety of a dropped server rack.
XML External Entity issues arose because parsers happily fetched external resources when told to, turning document processing into server-side mischief for anyone generous with markup.
Attackers often create new cloud identities after compromise so they can persist even if the original stolen account is reset, which is identity persistence wearing a respectable name badge.
Brand impersonation phishing works best when timing aligns with real business rhythms such as payroll, tax season or annual reviews, because relevance does much of the dirty work.
Serverless functions reduce some infrastructure overhead, but they also create new blind spots in logging, secret handling and permission boundaries if engineering assumes “managed” means “self-securing.”
Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman published Rivest–Shamir–Adleman in 1977, and the algorithm’s initials have launched more questionable compliance claims than they probably intended.
An online extortionist once demanded payment in gift cards, which sounds unserious until finance discovers somebody already bought them in a panic.
In the 1980s, phone phreaking blurred into early hacking culture, showing that telecom fraud and computer intrusion were neighbours long before they had separate conference tracks.
Shamoon, first seen in 2012, destroyed data by overwriting files and master boot records, making it memorable not for stealth but for a very firm opinion on availability.
Insecure deserialisation is dangerous because applications may reconstruct objects with side effects from untrusted data, which is a lovely example of software treating strangers like old colleagues.
Tools such as Cobalt Strike became heavily abused because offensive frameworks save adversaries time, and defenders tend to notice tooling popularity only after it has acquired a criminal fan club.
Evil-twin wireless networks still catch users because convenience can outrank suspicion, especially when the network name looks familiar and the coffee is already getting cold.
Public cloud storage buckets are not inherently insecure; making them public unintentionally is the insecure bit, though the bucket rarely gets equal billing in the post-incident write-up.
A digital signature proves integrity and origin only if the key can be trusted, which is why certificate compromise is so awkward and why trust stores deserve more affection than they get.
A researcher once received a bug-bounty dispute because the company claimed the vulnerable system was “out of scope” despite running the production login page, which is one way to define scope.
The first DEF CON took place in 1993, beginning as a one-off gathering and becoming one of the most recognisable security conferences, where half the content is serious and half is suspiciously cheerful.
NotPetya in 2017 masqueraded as ransomware but functioned more like a wiper, causing massive disruption through enterprise networks that discovered flatness is not just an architecture style.
Server-Side Request Forgery is especially nasty in cloud environments because the server can often reach things users cannot, including internal APIs and metadata endpoints that never expected to meet strangers.
Many human-operated ransomware cases begin with surprisingly mundane steps such as a stolen Virtual Private Network account, a weak remote-access path or an unmonitored legacy appliance.
Phishing kits increasingly include geofencing and anti-analysis checks so only likely victims see the lure, which is customer segmentation applied with deeply unfortunate intent.
Zero Trust is less a product than an argument against ambient trust, although marketing departments continue to treat it like a box they can ship with a subscription.
Hash collisions matter differently depending on the algorithm and use case; for example, MD5 and SHA-1 are broken for collision resistance, which is why trusting them for signatures became difficult to defend.
One chief executive was reportedly duped by an artificial-voice scam mimicking a senior colleague, which is a sobering reminder that social engineering happily adopts new transport layers.
The 1998 Solar Sunrise intrusions into United States military systems helped push cyber issues further into national-security discussions, even though the techniques were not especially exotic by modern standards.
TrickBot started in banking fraud and evolved into a modular platform for reconnaissance, credential theft and ransomware support, which is what happens when malware gets career development.
Buffer overflows remain infamous because writing past memory boundaries can corrupt execution flow, and memory remains distressingly obedient when told to store one byte too many.
Lateral movement often follows the path of least resistance rather than the path of greatest elegance, which is why neglected admin shares and reused local passwords remain depressingly relevant.
Thread-hijacking phishing succeeds because a victim sees a real subject line and familiar participants, then overlooks the subtle clue that the latest reply is carrying the moral quality of a trapdoor.
Secure boot adds value by verifying trusted code during startup, but if key management and firmware updates are weak, the chain of trust becomes more decorative than dependable.
Kerberos is strong when implemented properly, yet tickets and service accounts become attractive targets precisely because the protocol does a good job once trust has already been granted.
In one cryptocurrency heist investigation, suspects reportedly stored stolen funds in wallets named with obvious labels, because discretion is not uniformly distributed across the threat landscape.
The first website went live in 1991 at CERN, and its survival is oddly comforting given how many newer things break when you ask them to do precisely what they advertise.
Mirai, in 2016, built a botnet from internet-facing devices using default credentials and then launched large distributed denial-of-service attacks, proving that “smart” is not a security classification.
Path confusion and canonicalisation bugs crop up when software disagrees with itself about what a path or URL truly is, which is a more common identity crisis than it should be.
Adversaries often abuse remote-management tools such as AnyDesk or ScreenConnect because authorised software can look harmless until it begins arriving under highly unauthorised circumstances.
Most push-based authentication prompts are terrible at conveying context, so users are asked to approve something they did not start with a screen that radiates bland confidence.
Kubernetes is powerful, but misconfigured dashboards, overly permissive service accounts and exposed API servers have all featured in incidents where “orchestration” quickly became “forensics.”
The one-time pad is information-theoretically secure only if the key is truly random, at least as long as the message and never reused, which makes it brilliant and almost entirely impractical.
A laptop once sold on an online auction site reportedly still contained sensitive corporate data, proving asset disposal can fail long after endpoint protection says it is healthy.
The National Vulnerability Database and the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures system helped standardise vulnerability discussion, which was necessary because even chaos benefits from consistent naming.
Ryuk became known for targeting larger organisations and often arriving after precursor malware established access, because specialisation, regrettably, also exists in extortion.
Clickjacking tricks users into interacting with something different from what they see, which is basically user-interface design weaponised against consent.
Attackers commonly target backup systems and hypervisors late in an intrusion because recovery pain improves negotiating leverage in ways nobody mistakes for innovation.
Search Engine Optimisation poisoning places malicious or scam pages in search results so victims walk themselves into trouble, sparing the criminal the effort of crafting an email.
Certificate transparency logs are useful for spotting newly issued certificates, including suspicious ones, because defenders occasionally deserve a data source that is helpful before the incident report.
Security through obscurity is not entirely worthless, but it collapses the moment obscurity stops obscuring, which history suggests happens at a rate bordering on impatience.
One man was jailed after sending bomb-hoax emails via accounts tied to his own infrastructure, which is the sort of attribution shortcut investigators quietly appreciate.
The 1986 Brain virus originated in Pakistan and targeted floppy-disk boot sectors, becoming a famous example of how self-replication moved from theory into everyday inconvenience.
REvil, also known as Sodinokibi, popularised high-profile double-extortion operations and affiliate-based ransomware, effectively franchising disruption with ghastly efficiency.
Race conditions occur when timing changes the security outcome, meaning a system can be secure, insecure or both depending on which thread wins a sprint nobody authorised.
Data staging before exfiltration remains common because moving files into a convenient location simplifies packaging and transfer, which is another reason odd archive creation deserves suspicion.
Phishing simulation works best when followed by useful feedback rather than ritual humiliation; making users resent the security team is a poor defensive architecture.
Single Sign-On improves usability and can improve security, but compromise the identity provider and you have achieved the scaling advantages attackers usually only dream about.
Message Authentication Codes protect integrity and authenticity with a shared secret, which is excellent until someone forgets the “shared secret” bit and stores it where everyone can admire it.
Fraudsters have sent fake legal notices to domain owners claiming trademark infringement, then offered convenient settlement links that mostly settled victims’ bank balances.
The 1990s saw the rise of widespread dial-up bulletin boards, warez culture and early malware exchange communities, proving collaboration platforms were risky long before Teams joined the argument.
QakBot spent years evolving from banking trojan to malware distribution and intrusion-enabler, surviving takedowns and rebuilding because resilient criminal infrastructure is an unpleasantly recurring theme.
Format-string bugs can let attackers leak memory or write values by abusing unsafe logging and output functions, which is an impressively rude way for text formatting to become dangerous.
Many post-compromise playbooks include enumerating trust relationships, remote shares and backup paths before domain-wide action, because ransomware crews also perform due diligence, sadly.
Multi-Factor Authentication bypass sometimes boils down to session theft rather than factor defeat, which changes the lesson from “use more maths” to “protect the whole session lifecycle.”
Egress filtering matters because exfiltration and command-and-control both need outbound paths; defenders who only stare at inbound traffic are essentially guarding half a door.
PGP, created by Phil Zimmermann in 1991, made strong encryption broadly accessible to individuals, which was politically contentious and mathematically rather effective.
A fake “tax refund” portal once displayed a mismatched logo, wrong colours and a footer from an unrelated florist, yet still caught victims because urgency routinely beats aesthetics.
The 2007 Estonia cyber attacks pushed distributed denial-of-service into mainstream geopolitical discussion, even if the technical means were less novel than the strategic signalling.
DarkComet and other Remote Access Trojans became popular partly because inexpensive off-the-shelf remote-control malware lowers the entry barrier for actors who have ambition but limited engineering.
XXE and insecure parser behaviour fade when secure defaults are enforced, which is why so much secure engineering work consists of preventing software from being enthusiastically unwise.
Adversaries often abuse cloud collaboration features for exfiltration, including shared links and synchronised drives, because sanctioned workflows make unpleasantly good hiding places.
Voice phishing, or vishing, uses urgency and authority cues especially well because the victim has less time to inspect details and more pressure to keep the conversation moving.
Infrastructure as Code can improve security if review and policy checks exist, but codifying a mistake merely gives it version control and a nicer deployment story.
Entropy in cryptography is about unpredictability, not complexity theatre; a long but predictable password is still just a predictable password with a gym membership.
One ransomware victim reportedly printed the ransom note and faxed it to another office for advice, which is not ideal incident handling but is at least admirably tangible.
The term “hacker” originally carried a more positive, exploratory meaning in computing culture before media usage narrowed it toward intrusion, which is how language behaves when panic gets a microphone.
Dridex specialised in banking credential theft and later acted as a loader for broader compromises, showing how financially motivated malware often matures into full-service access delivery.
Insecure Direct Object Reference flaws happen when access control trusts the identifier alone, allowing users to request other users’ records by changing an id and keeping a straight face.
Command-and-control channels increasingly use common cloud platforms or social media because defenders are understandably hesitant to block half the internet on a speculative Tuesday.
QR-code menus, parking notices and package slips created a handy social-engineering surface because people are now trained to treat random squares as gateways to legitimacy.
The Domain Name System can use DNSSEC to add integrity assurances, though deployment is uneven enough that its benefits sometimes feel like a well-kept secret.
Side-channel attacks do not break the algorithm directly; they exploit timing, power usage or other leakage around it, because implementation details often resent being treated as details.
A phishing gang once used an obviously fake company name that translated roughly to “Totally Real Delivery Service,” and still saw enough clicks to justify everyone’s cynicism.
The 2014 Sony Pictures breach mixed data theft, destructive activity and coercive leaks, showing that cyber incidents can have business, legal and geopolitical dimensions all at once.
Agent Tesla has long been traded as a commodity infostealer focused on credentials and clipboard data, proving low-cost malware can remain effective if it embraces unglamorous reliability.
Prototype pollution in JavaScript can let attackers affect application behaviour by modifying inherited properties, which is a niche phrase for a very broad headache.
Attackers frequently enumerate Active Directory because it provides the relationship map, privilege landscape and naming conventions needed to turn one access point into a proper estate tour.
A convincing phish often borrows internal vocabulary, formatting and calendar timing from the target organisation, which is why leaked emails and public documents are so operationally helpful to adversaries.
SaaS security is rarely about one giant flaw; it is usually about permissions, integrations, stale accounts and logging gaps combining into the sort of visibility puzzle analysts adore less than they claim.
The birthday paradox matters in hash collision discussions because collision probability rises surprisingly quickly as sample size grows, which is one of those mathematical jokes nobody requested.
One cybercriminal was identified after posting screenshots that included his desktop username, proving redaction remains a premium service even in the underworld.
The first webcam, at Cambridge in 1991, monitored a coffee pot rather than a missile silo, which feels reassuring until you remember how many internet-connected cameras came after.
Locky, prominent in 2016, spread through malicious attachments and demand notes, helping establish ransomware’s office-product aesthetic: invoice lures outside, cryptographic misery inside.
CRLF injection can let attackers manipulate headers or logs by smuggling carriage return and line feed characters, which is how punctuation occasionally becomes an accomplice.
Privilege escalation often succeeds not through exotic kernel wizardry but through weak service permissions, stale local admin rights or badly scoped automation accounts.
Browser-in-the-Browser phishing presents fake login pop-ups inside a page, relying on users trusting the look of the window rather than the origin, which is exactly the sort of visual trick that ages badly.
Identity providers are now crown jewels because federated access concentrates trust, so identity telemetry often tells the breach story earlier than endpoint logs do.
The Data Encryption Standard, standardised in 1977, was hugely influential despite later key-length concerns, and it helped move practical cryptography from specialist circles into mainstream systems.
Fake technical-support scammers have convinced victims to install remote-access tools and then charged them to fix non-existent infections, which is banal, effective and spectacularly irritating.
The 2015 and 2016 Ukraine power-grid incidents showed that cyber operations could disrupt electricity distribution, though the human operators and recovery processes mattered just as much as the malware headlines.
Mimikatz became notorious because extracting credentials and abusing authentication material is extremely useful once a system is compromised, and credential hygiene is rarely as clean as policy suggests.
HTTP request smuggling exploits parsing differences between front-end and back-end servers, turning normal-looking traffic into desynchronised trouble whose root cause everyone initially denies.
Ransomware crews often spend days or weeks inside a network before detonation, locating backups and privileged systems first, because surprise is far more valuable when it is well prepared.
Fake captchas and “download to continue” prompts increasingly deliver malware because users have been trained to click through friction as if scepticism were an accessibility bug.
Telemetry pipelines need their own security thinking; if logs can be disabled, delayed or flooded cheaply, your visibility fabric becomes a denial-of-sight problem.
A stream cipher is only as safe as its keystream uniqueness; reuse a nonce or key in the wrong design and the maths starts writing your breach report for you.
One man allegedly laundered cybercrime proceeds through an online pet-supplies business, which sounds niche until you recall that “miscellaneous retail” has hidden many sins.
The 1988 Morris Worm also led to the creation of the Computer Emergency Response Team Coordination Center, because after enough chaos institutions usually discover a fondness for coordination.
BlackEnergy evolved from botnet malware into a tool used in more targeted intrusions, including activity linked to critical infrastructure, proving commodity roots do not prevent strategic ambition.
SSRF is often underestimated because the vulnerable server is making the request, which tempts people to call it “just fetching a URL” right up until it fetches internal secrets.
Attackers abuse trust in remote-monitoring and management tools because those platforms already have broad access, signed binaries and an established place in change windows.
Payroll redirection fraud works by changing salary account details at exactly the moment the finance process expects a mundane administrative request, which is a very ordinary route to an extraordinary complaint.
Object storage versioning can save incidents from becoming disasters, though it is less comforting when the attacker also found the policy settings and the delete permissions.
Hashcat is a defensive tool in the right hands because password auditing benefits from realistic cracking speed, but it also demonstrates why weak password policy is mostly decorative.
A fake “sextortion” email is often built entirely from recycled breach data and bluff, which makes it both low-effort and oddly effective against recipients with no reason to trust their own calm.
RFC 1149, the April Fools’ specification for transmitting internet protocol over avian carriers, is still cited because security people cannot resist a standards joke with packet loss baked in.
BazarLoader often arrived through themed lures and call-back phishing, illustrating that social engineering and malware delivery remain close colleagues even when the naming conventions change.
Remote code execution is not a vulnerability class so much as a consequence, which is why hearing “there’s an RCE” should immediately prompt the more useful question, “caused by what exactly.”
Adversaries frequently create or abuse Group Policy Objects after domain compromise because centralised administration is wonderfully efficient for both IT and criminal devastation.
Account-takeover attempts often begin with password-spraying rather than brute force because low-and-slow guesses across many accounts evade controls better than hammering one target to death.
Cloud-native logging can be excellent, but only if retention, centralisation and parser quality are handled properly; otherwise you end up with a distributed archive of almost-helpful regret.
The padlock icon never meant a site was trustworthy, only that transport was encrypted, but users kept reading it as moral approval anyway.
A scammer once forgot to remove the placeholder text “insert fake invoice number here,” which should have ended the campaign but apparently only reduced its conversion rate.
The Melissa and ILOVEYOU era helped normalise attachment paranoia, teaching a generation that novelty and urgency in subject lines usually come with technical strings attached.
Clop became especially visible through mass data-theft events exploiting file-transfer software, underlining how extortion can scale nicely when one trusted product feeds many victims.
Use-after-free bugs occur when code accesses memory after it has been released, turning stale pointers into active risk and memory safety into a deeply personal discussion.
Data exfiltration over uncommon protocols or odd destinations stands out for a reason; a thermostat talking like a media streamer is the kind of sentence analysts should not have to write twice.
Shipping notifications, document shares and voicemail alerts remain top phishing themes because they align with routine business noise and exploit users’ urge to clear queues quickly.
Hypervisors narrow some attack paths but create a high-value layer where misconfiguration or escape issues can affect multiple guests at once, which is what concentration risk looks like in infrastructure.
Certificate pinning can improve resistance to rogue certificates in some scenarios, though operational complexity and ecosystem changes have made its use a matter for careful design rather than reflex.
In one fraud case, call-centre scammers read from scripts that included stage directions such as “sound sympathetic here,” which feels theatrical until treasury says the payment already left.
Network intrusion detection grew significantly in the 1990s, but signature logic quickly met its limits once attackers realised changing a few bytes was cheaper than changing behaviour.
Tiny Banker Trojan, also known as Tinba, demonstrated that effective banking malware did not need to be large; compact code can still cause outsized damage if the target selection is sensible.
Cross-Site Request Forgery abuses a user’s authenticated browser to send unwanted actions, which is less about stealing credentials and more about borrowing them without so much as a thank-you.
Not all persistence is technical; attackers also create dependency by compromising processes, suppliers or communication channels so remediation becomes a business problem before it becomes a clean-up plan.
Multi-channel phishing, where email is followed by a call or SMS, is effective because repetition creates legitimacy and because victims assume criminals would not bother with admin.
Secrets management platforms help, but hard-coded keys still turn up in repositories, build scripts and chat messages because developers remain excellent at solving today’s problem enthusiastically.
A cryptographic nonce is meant to be used once; violate that, and otherwise respectable algorithms can behave like they were designed by a committee in a hurry.
One extortion email claimed the sender had installed malware through the victim’s smart refrigerator, which was absurd enough that several recipients phoned IT just to ask whether fridges had become strategic.
In 2004, Google announced Gmail with one gigabyte of storage, which felt implausibly generous at the time and incidentally created more room for suspicious attachments to linger.
Bumblebee emerged as a malware loader delivered through themed lures and often discussed as a replacement in familiar criminal workflows, because the access economy dislikes gaps in the market.
Integer overflows matter because arithmetic limits can quietly produce smaller buffers or wrong bounds, and computers are distressingly literal about impossible numbers.
Threat actors commonly test security tooling by dropping harmless files, running whoami-style commands or checking for defensive processes before betting the intrusion on something noisier.
Push notifications that include app name, location and device context are harder to abuse than generic “approve sign-in” prompts, which is the sort of user-experience detail security only notices after pain.
Software Bills of Materials are useful for understanding dependency exposure, though they are not a patch by themselves and do not magically make transitive risk feel less transitive.
Zero-knowledge proofs let one party prove a statement without revealing the secret behind it, which sounds magical until you meet the algebra and discover it is merely very disciplined cleverness.
A phishing page once offered “secure sign in with company logo verified,” apparently unaware that logos are easier to copy than morals.
The 2020 SolarWinds compromise made supply-chain risk painfully concrete by abusing trusted software updates, showing that signed code can still deliver a horribly unsigned outcome.
Initial access malware such as loaders and stealers often earns more criminal value as a prelude than as an end state, because access resale keeps the underground oddly liquid.
Regular expression denial of service can occur when badly designed patterns consume huge processing time on crafted input, giving punctuation and repetition far more power than they deserve.
Attackers frequently target directory services, identity stores and federation links because compromising trust relationships scales better than compromising endpoints one by one.
Lookalike domains exploiting homograph characters can fool users because many scripts contain visually similar letters, turning typography into a minor but effective accomplice.
Edge and branch networking gear are high-value targets because they bridge users, traffic and management access; insecure appliances have created more than one estate-wide security lesson.
Transport Layer Security replaced Secure Sockets Layer in practice years ago, yet people still say “SSL” generically, which is one of several naming habits protocols have given up correcting.
One offender was reportedly traced because he reused the same recovery phone number across fake accounts, proving that convenience remains a strong attribution signal.
