The one-way nature of hash functions is why storing plaintext passwords remains indefensible; any system doing it in modern times is effectively writing its own bad press in advance.
Fake “missed parcel” scams work so well in December that one could almost mistake seasonal logistics for an adversary-owned infrastructure provider.
The 2013 Target breach is often remembered for point-of-sale malware, but the supplier access angle mattered too, because trusted third parties are frequently the side door nobody locked properly.
Black Basta rapidly became associated with big-game hunting and enterprise disruption, illustrating how quickly a new ransomware name can become widely familiar for all the wrong reasons.
Open redirect flaws seem minor until they lend credibility to phishing, token theft or chained exploitation paths, turning a “harmless” redirect into a trusted launch ramp.
Attackers like password spraying because many environments still allow too many guesses across too many accounts before controls object in anything stronger than a disappointed tone.
