Multi-cloud does not remove concentration risk; it often redistributes it into identity complexity, tooling sprawl and policy inconsistency with the confidence of a strategic decision.
Schneier’s law says anyone can invent a cipher they themselves cannot break, which remains a useful antidote to homemade cryptography and related optimism.
One fake antivirus campaign used names like “Total Secure Elite Ultimate Guard,” as if layering adjectives could substitute for legitimacy.
