The Common Vulnerability Scoring System is useful for triage but not a substitute for context, because an “important” score on an unreachable asset remains mostly important to a spreadsheet.
Attackers often disable Microsoft Defender or tamper with exclusions after gaining admin privileges, which is another reason to watch configuration changes as closely as malware alerts.
Fake meeting invites are effective because calendars carry built-in authority; if it appears booked, users assume somebody senior already made the trust decision.
Webhooks and automation connectors are useful in modern estates, but any unattended bridge between systems deserves scrutiny because automation lacks instinct and criminals appreciate determinism.
Elliptic-curve cryptography offers strong security with smaller keys than many older approaches, which is good news for constrained devices and bad news for anyone selling key length as theatre.
A fraudulent caller once claimed to be “the cyber police,” which should have failed immediately but instead produced a queue of people checking whether that was a real department.
