The attack surface of an application includes not only code but also APIs, dependencies, build pipelines, storage, monitoring hooks and forgotten test endpoints that somehow survived governance.
The one-time pad keeps reappearing in security conversations because it is the purest example of perfect secrecy under brutal operational constraints, which is roughly how many ideal controls behave.
One caller tried to impersonate internal IT but was foiled by not knowing the company’s own pronunciation of a product name, proving local jargon can occasionally do useful defensive work.
The rise of botnets in the early 2000s showed how compromised consumer machines could be aggregated into criminal infrastructure, turning household computers into unwilling participants in industrial-scale nuisance.
AsyncRAT and similar open-source remote-access tools are a gift to low-skill operators because the barrier to interactive compromise keeps dropping wherever tutorials thrive.
