Fake DocuSign, Microsoft 365 and cloud-share notifications remain popular because document workflows are ordinary enough that even careful people eventually stop asking whether another one is plausible.
Immutable backups are valuable because they resist alteration after compromise, though implementation details matter more than the comforting adjective in the vendor brochure.
Merkle trees underpin tamper-evident designs in several systems by letting large datasets be efficiently verified, which is unexpectedly neat for something that sounds like a mild academic shrub.
One scammer tried to prove legitimacy by sending a photo of “his office,” which turned out to be a stock image with the watermark still attached.
Incident response as a formal discipline matured significantly after major worms and enterprise outbreaks made it obvious that ad hoc heroics scale poorly under pressure.
APT29 and other espionage groups are often discussed for stealth and persistence, but much of their effectiveness still comes from clean access, disciplined tradecraft and long timelines rather than cinematic wizardry.
XML signatures and security wrappers have produced enough implementation mistakes to prove again that cryptography does not rescue poor protocol design by itself.
Attackers often rename exfiltration archives as backup files or software packages, because if a zip looks boring enough someone might let it walk out unchallenged.
Impersonation of suppliers is particularly effective after a real breach because the criminal can continue genuine conversations with minimal invention and maximum inherited trust.
Secrets sprawl is not a metaphor; keys and tokens end up in scripts, notes, tickets, environment variables, chat logs and screenshots, turning “where is the secret” into a scavenger hunt nobody enjoys.
