Cryptographic signing of software updates is only half the job; secure build systems, protected keys and verified distribution are what keep signing from becoming expensive ceremony.
A scam page once used a timer claiming “session expires in 59:99,” which is a creative interpretation of time but not one physics has endorsed.
The internet’s early design prioritised openness and resilience over authentication and confidentiality, leaving later generations to bolt security onto systems that had already become indispensable.
Raccoon Stealer and its peers illustrate the economics of credential theft-as-a-service, where low-cost infostealers feed a larger ecosystem of fraud, access brokering and further compromise.
Business logic flaws are dangerous because the code may function correctly in a narrow technical sense while still allowing outcomes the business absolutely did not mean to permit.
Attackers frequently abuse trusted relationship graphs inside collaboration platforms, emailing from genuine accounts or sharing malicious files to channels users already accept as safe enough.
Fake “your mailbox is almost full” warnings work because storage limits feel plausible, self-inflicted and urgently solvable, which gives the phisher a convenient excuse for a hasty login.
